Andr. ii. 2. l. —- Quid hoc morbi est ? ‘⁶ What strange disease is this ’.Μ These are the words of Parmeno after Phaedria is gone, reflecting with himself upon what he had observed in his master. He had known him a man of spirit, prudence, andfim ness3 apt to give in to none of the follies and rash projects of other young men of the like age. He sees him now all irresolution and inconstancy, never continuing a moment in the same mind3 and this entirely owing to his passion for Thais. He had therefore reason to eall love a disease, which could produce so sudden a change in the temper, and so totally enfeeble and unman the soul. Comp. Andr. i. 2. 22.
